      <article class="article language-panel" lang="en" data-language-panel="en">
        <section id="bottom-line" aria-labelledby="bottom-line-heading">
          <h2 id="bottom-line-heading">Overview</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>9 July</strong> is Argentina's <strong>Día de la Independencia</strong>: a winter national holiday that commemorates the declaration made in San Miguel de Tucumán on <strong>9 July 1816</strong> by the <strong>Congreso de Tucumán</strong>. The deputies declared the <strong>Provincias Unidas en Sud América</strong> (United Provinces in South America) independent of Spain; days later they added a break with any other foreign domination (<a href="https://www.educ.ar/recursos/132481/9-de-julio-dia-de-la-declaracion-de-la-independencia" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Educ.ar</a>; <a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Declaraci%C3%B3n_de_independencia_de_la_Argentina" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Acta / Wikipedia</a>). Under <a href="https://www.argentina.gob.ar/normativa/nacional/ley-27399-281835/texto" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Ley 27.399</a> (2017), the date is an immovable national holiday (<em>feriado nacional inamovible</em>).
          </p>
          <p>
            Official commemorations usually center on Tucumán and the <a href="https://www.argentina.gob.ar/capital-humano/cultura/monumentos/museo-casa-historica-de-la-independencia" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Casa Histórica</a>: Te Deum, flag raising, civic-military parade, presidential attendance in most years. Across the country people eat winter dishes, especially <strong>locro</strong>, and schools run pageants and flag ceremonies. Argentina also keeps <strong>25 May</strong> (the May Revolution of 1810) as a major patriotic holiday; the two dates are often mentioned together and sometimes mixed up (<a href="https://www.lanacion.com.ar/lifestyle/por-que-recordamos-mas-revolucion-mayo-nid2265816/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">La Nación</a>). Historian <a href="https://www.lanacion.com.ar/cultura/25-de-mayo-preguntas-y-respuestas-para-entender-los-sucesos-de-una-semana-historica-nid19052021/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Daniel Balmaceda</a> puts the difference as <strong>autonomy</strong> in 1810 versus <strong>independence and sovereignty</strong> in 1816.
          </p>
          <p>
            The rest of this page covers how the declaration came about, who was in the room (and who was not), what happened to the holiday afterward, and a few myths that need qualifying. Later governments reused 9 July for their own projects (Rivadavia 1826, Rosas 1835, Perón 1947, Operativo Independencia 1975, recent administrations). The Casa Histórica itself was mostly demolished in 1903–04 and reconstructed in 1943.
          </p>
          <blockquote>
            <p>
              <em>Sources: the Acta text; Educ.ar's independence overview; argentina.gob.ar heritage pages; Marcela Ternavasio, <cite>Historia de la Argentina, 1806–1852</cite> (Siglo XXI), for territorial sovereignty and May/July holiday hierarchy; plus Balmaceda, Pigna, Páez de la Torre (h) and del Carril. Contested numbers are ranges. Inline links point to sources used.</em>
            </p>
          </blockquote>
        </section>

        <section id="key-findings" aria-labelledby="key-findings-heading">
          <h2 id="key-findings-heading">Findings</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>The distinction</strong>: 25 May 1810 (May Revolution / Primera Junta, in Buenos Aires) = <em>autonomy</em> under the "mask of Ferdinand VII"; 9 July 1816 (Congreso de Tucumán) = <em>formal independence and sovereignty</em>. Conflating them is common in public speech (<a href="https://www.lanacion.com.ar/cultura/25-de-mayo-preguntas-y-respuestas-para-entender-los-sucesos-de-una-semana-historica-nid19052021/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">La Nación</a>).
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>The declared entity was "las Provincias Unidas en Sud América,"</strong> not "Argentina": a larger territory that then included the Alto Perú (today Bolivia). The phrase <strong>"y de toda otra dominación extranjera"</strong> ("and of all other foreign domination") was not in the 9 July text; it was added on <strong>19 July 1816</strong> in secret session, on Pedro Medrano's motion, after rumors that leaders meant to hand the country to Portugal or Britain (<a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Declaraci%C3%B3n_de_independencia_de_la_Argentina" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Wikipedia</a>; <a href="https://elhistoriador.com.ar/9-de-julio-de-1816-declaracion-de-la-independencia/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">El Historiador</a>).
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>The Acta was signed by 29 deputies</strong> (of roughly 33–34 elected). The Litoral provinces under Artigas boycotted; several Alto Perú cities were under realist control; Paraguay declined. It was printed in <strong>Spanish, Quechua and Aymara</strong> (<a href="https://www.argentina.gob.ar/interior/archivo-general-de-la-nacion/traducciones-de-la-independencia" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">AGN</a>).
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Form of government left open</strong>: many deputies favored constitutional monarchy; Belgrano proposed crowning a descendant of the Incas at Cuzco, with support from San Martín and Güemes; porteño opposition, candidate problems and documented racist objections helped kill the plan. A durable republican constitution came in 1853 (<a href="https://elhistoriador.com.ar/el-congreso-de-tucuman-y-la-declaracion-de-la-independencia-por-felipe-pigna/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">El Historiador</a>; <a href="https://www.educ.ar/recursos/130847/belgrano-y-el-proyecto-de-monarquia-incaica/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">educ.ar</a>).
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>The building is a 1943 reconstruction</strong>, not original fabric; the "little house" (<em>casita</em>) image is largely an artifact of the 1904 <em>Templete</em> (<a href="https://www.argentina.gob.ar/capital-humano/cultura/monumentos/museo-casa-historica-de-la-independencia" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">argentina.gob.ar</a>; <a href="https://www.lagaceta.com.ar/nota/691339/sociedad/historia-casa-tucuman-entro-historia.html" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">La Gaceta</a>).
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Holiday reuse</strong>: documented from Rosas's 1835 equalization decree through Perón 1947, Macri 2016 and Milei's 2024 <a href="https://chequeado.com/el-explicador/a-un-ano-de-la-firma-del-pacto-de-mayo-el-chequeo-a-los-10-compromisos-del-acuerdo-que-hizo-javier-milei-con-los-gobernadores/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Pacto de Mayo</a> and 2025 cancellation (<a href="https://tn.com.ar/politica/2025/07/08/debido-a-la-niebla-javier-milei-no-viajara-a-tucuman-por-el-9-de-julio/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">TN</a>).
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Not all of "Argentina" voted</strong>: Educ.ar notes the Congress opened with 33 deputies from a territory unlike today's Argentina. Charcas (today Bolivia) sent representation; Entre Ríos, Corrientes and Santa Fe stayed out with Artigas's Liga (<a href="https://www.educ.ar/recursos/132481/9-de-julio-dia-de-la-declaracion-de-la-independencia" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Educ.ar</a>).
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>May 25 often ranked higher</strong>: Fiestas Mayas began in 1811 and were never cancelled; after 1816, Fiestas Julias were added, but May usually kept pride of place in the Río de la Plata festive calendar, especially in Buenos Aires (Ternavasio; <a href="https://www.educ.ar/recursos/130924/un-pais-con-dos-fechas-patrias" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Educ.ar interview</a>).
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Naming came later</strong>: 1816 = Provincias Unidas en Sud América; 1826 constitution used "República Argentina" but failed; the durable constitutional settlement is 1853–1860 (<a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Provincias_Unidas_del_R%C3%ADo_de_la_Plata" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Wikipedia</a>; <a href="https://repositorio.uca.edu.ar/bitstream/123456789/10002/1/sobre-denominaciones-republica-argentina.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">UCA on denominations</a>).
            </li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="part-i" aria-labelledby="part-i-heading">
          <h2 id="part-i-heading">Part I — How Argentina became independent</h2>

          
          <h3 id="before-1810">Before 1810: a viceroyalty, not "Argentina"</h3>
          <p>
            The schoolbook story often starts in May 1810. The institutional background starts earlier. In 1776 the Spanish Crown created the <a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virreinato_del_R%C3%ADo_de_la_Plata" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Viceroyalty of the Río de la Plata</a> with Buenos Aires as capital, grouping jurisdictions that today cover Argentina, Uruguay, Paraguay and Bolivia. Ternavasio stresses that this was not yet a natural Argentine unit: it was a heterogeneous imperial space with changing borders and competing territorial loyalties.
          </p>
          <p>
            The <a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Invasiones_inglesas" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">British invasions of 1806–1807</a> matter because they exposed the weakness of Spanish authority and militarized Buenos Aires society. The city defended itself, gained political confidence and grew used to acting on its own before the formal May Revolution. Ternavasio also notes that Buenos Aires still behaved more like the center of a local governorship than the real capital of a huge integrated viceroyalty, until May 1810 forced it to try to command that space.
          </p>

          <h3 id="may-revolution">1810: autonomy, not independence</h3>
          <p>
            The chain of events began not in Buenos Aires but in Europe. In 1808 Napoleon Bonaparte invaded Spain, forced the abdications of Carlos IV and Fernando VII and installed his brother Joseph on the Spanish throne. Spanish resistance juntas governed in Fernando's name; as they collapsed one by one, the legitimacy of colonial authorities in America collapsed with them. When news reached Buenos Aires in May 1810 that the Junta of Seville (the last major seat of Spanish resistance) had fallen, the criollos of Buenos Aires forced the issue.
          </p>
          <p>
            During the <strong>Semana de Mayo</strong> (18–25 May 1810), a <em>cabildo abierto</em> (open town council) on 22 May voted to depose Viceroy Baltasar Hidalgo de Cisneros and on 25 May the <strong>Primera Junta</strong> was installed, presided over by Cornelio Saavedra, with Mariano Moreno and Juan José Paso as secretaries and Manuel Belgrano, Juan José Castelli, Miguel de Azcuénaga, Domingo Matheu, Juan Larrea and Manuel Alberti as members.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Junta declared it governed "in the name of Sr. D. Fernando VII" (the famous <strong>"máscara de Fernando VII"</strong> / "mask of Ferdinand VII"). The legal theory often invoked was <a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Retroversi%C3%B3n_de_la_soberan%C3%ADa_de_los_pueblos" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">retroversión de la soberanía</a>: with the king captive and the imperial order collapsing, sovereignty reverted to the <em>pueblos</em>. Ternavasio notes that "pueblo"/"pueblos" did not mean "the Argentine people" as a single nation; they could mean cities, provinces or local corporate communities claiming their own rights (<a href="https://www.conicet.gov.ar/repensar-la-independencia/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">CONICET / Ternavasio interview</a>). Early 1810 looks less like "Argentina vs Spain" and more like a fight over who had the right to govern the ruins of the old viceroyalty. Either way, <strong>no independence was declared in 1810</strong>. Educ.ar frames 9 July as the first explicit will of emancipation after the political process begun in May (<a href="https://www.educ.ar/recursos/132481/9-de-julio-dia-de-la-declaracion-de-la-independencia" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Educ.ar</a>).
          </p>
          <p>
            Later historiography (including Mitre's) often read 1810 as already independentist; the Congress's own 1817 <em>Manifiesto a las Naciones</em> described the 1810 Junta as provisional and in Fernando's name (<a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Declaraci%C3%B3n_de_independencia_de_la_Argentina" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Wikipedia summary of the Manifiesto</a>).
          </p>

          
          <h3 id="buenos-aires-claim">Buenos Aires tries to inherit the viceroyalty</h3>
          <p>
            Ternavasio's point is sharper: after May 1810 Buenos Aires tried to make the old viceroyalty obey the revolutionary government seated in Buenos Aires, and only then discovered what its capital claim actually required (support from jurisdictions it had not previously needed to command in the same way). Paraguay, the Banda Oriental, Upper Peru and the Litoral do not fit a tidy national story for that reason: Paraguay's autonomy became a point of no return; the Banda Oriental and Litoral tied themselves to Artigas's federal/confederal alternative; Upper Peru remained militarily unstable.
          </p>
          <p>
            Ternavasio titles the early conflict in terms of civil war as much as anti-Spanish war: communities, cities, provinces, royalists, autonomists, centralists and federalists fought inside the collapsing Spanish monarchy. The tidy "patriots vs Spain" framing becomes available only later.
          </p>

          <h3 id="six-years">Six years of war and quarrel (1810–1816)</h3>
          <p>
            The years between are not a story of a country patiently waiting to declare something it had already decided. They were years of military campaigning and internal conflict between centralist (Buenos Aires) and confederationist tendencies across the former Viceroyalty of the Río de la Plata.
          </p>
          <p>What happened next:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>Military campaigns</strong>: Belgrano's Paraguay and Banda Oriental campaigns; the creation of the flag (1812); Belgrano's victories at Tucumán (1812) and Salta (1813); but then catastrophic defeats in the Alto Perú (Vilcapugio and Ayohuma, 1813), which ended hopes of holding what is today Bolivia.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>The Asamblea del Año XIII</strong> (1813), a failed almost-independence: abolished the oath of fidelity to Fernando VII, decreed freedom of the press, "freedom of wombs" (freeing children of slaves), abolished the <em>mita</em>, <em>yanaconazgo</em> and Indian tribute and suppressed noble titles, but it did <strong>not</strong> declare independence or write a constitution. Ternavasio reads it as exposing unresolved problems left by the monarchical crisis: Ferdinand's restoration, American war fronts and conflict with Artigas kept the revolutionary order unstable. So 9 July 1816 was not random; ambiguity had become untenable.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>1814</strong>: Fernando VII was restored to the Spanish throne, immediately repudiated the liberal Cádiz Constitution of 1812 and set about reconquering the American colonies by force. A large expeditionary force under General Pablo Morillo ("El Pacificador") was assembled, originally aimed in part at the Río de la Plata. Across Spanish America, 1815 was a year of patriot defeats.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>The internal rupture</strong>: the Litoral provinces and the Banda Oriental, under José Gervasio Artigas and his <strong>Liga de los Pueblos Libres</strong> (League of Free Peoples), broke with Buenos Aires' centralism. Buenos Aires forces sacked Santa Fe and Rosario in 1815; the Portuguese invaded the Banda Oriental in 1816. This split is why those provinces would boycott the Congress of Tucumán.
            </li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            By early 1816 the revolution faced realist pressure from the north and west, Portuguese pressure from the east and civil conflict with the Litoral. That military and political context is part of why the Congress moved to a formal declaration (<a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Congreso_de_Tucum%C3%A1n" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Congreso de Tucumán</a>).
          </p>

          <h3 id="why-tucuman">Why Tucumán, and not Buenos Aires</h3>
          <p>
            After the April 1815 revolution that overthrew Director Supremo Carlos María de Alvear, the provinces demanded a General Constituent Congress. The 1815 <em>Estatuto Provisional</em> set the rules and deliberately set the venue in the interior.
          </p>
          <p>The reasons, per historian Carlos Páez de la Torre (h) and others:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Geography</strong>: San Miguel de Tucumán sat roughly at the center of the territory of the United Provinces (which then extended deep into the Alto Perú).</li>
            <li><strong>Military protection</strong>: it was the headquarters of the Ejército del Norte (Army of the North), and Belgrano's 1812 victory there had secured it.</li>
            <li><strong>Distance from Artigas</strong>: it was far from the influence of the federalist Litoral.</li>
            <li>
              <strong>Anti-porteño symbolism</strong>: the interior provinces distrusted Buenos Aires' concentration of power. The Asamblea del Año XIII, held in Buenos Aires, had disappointed them by failing to declare independence. Choosing Tucumán signaled that independence would be a decision of the <em>provinces</em>, not an imposition of the port city. Buenos Aires itself did not push to host, so as not to antagonize the federalist military that had just overthrown Alvear.
            </li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            On 25 September 1816, by a vote reported as roughly 28 to 4, the Congress voted to move to Buenos Aires (where it sat from 1817 until dissolution in 1820), issuing a "Manifesto of Transfer" that said the seat changed without changing intention (<a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Congreso_de_Tucum%C3%A1n" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Wikipedia</a>).
          </p>

          <h3 id="deputies">The deputies (<em>congresales</em>): who they were, who was missing</h3>
          <p>
            The Congress opened its sessions on <strong>24 March 1816</strong>. Each province elected roughly one deputy per 15,000 inhabitants, via a two-stage indirect vote. <a href="https://www.educ.ar/recursos/132481/9-de-julio-dia-de-la-declaracion-de-la-independencia" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Educ.ar</a> states the sessions began with <strong>33 deputies</strong> present from a territory unlike today's Argentina. Other secondary sources give ~33–34 elected over the Congress's life and sometimes ~21 present on opening day; treat the opening-day figure as contested, the Educ.ar "33" as the clearest official-education count.
          </p>
          <p>
            The presidency rotated monthly; the two secretaries were <strong>Juan José Paso</strong> and <strong>José Mariano Serrano</strong>. The Congress also created <em>El Redactor del Congreso Nacional</em>, a periodical to publish the debates. On 3 May 1816 it named <strong>Juan Martín de Pueyrredón</strong> (deputy for San Luis) as Director Supremo, the national executive.
          </p>
          <p>
            The composition was strikingly clerical and legal: of the deputies, a large share were priests and lawyers. Accounts vary, but roughly <strong>11 or 12 of the 29 signers were clergy</strong> (nearly 40%), and around 17–18 were lawyers; a handful were military men.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Provinces represented</strong>: Buenos Aires, Catamarca, Córdoba, Jujuy, La Rioja, Mendoza, Salta, San Juan, San Luis, Santiago del Estero, Tucumán, plus the Alto Perú districts of Charcas, Chichas and Mizque (and Tarija, via a substitute).
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Provinces absent (the boycott)</strong>: The Liga Federal provinces under Artigas (the Banda Oriental, Corrientes, Entre Ríos, Misiones and Santa Fe) did <strong>not</strong> send deputies, because they were effectively at civil war with the Buenos Aires central government. (Córdoba, though sympathetic to the League, did send deputies.) Several Alto Perú cities (La Paz, Cochabamba, Potosí, Santa Cruz) could not send representatives because they had been reconquered by the realists. <strong>Paraguay</strong>, already governing itself autonomously under Dr. Francia, declined the invitation as "insulting."
          </p>
          <p>Other people who mattered, beyond the deputies:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Francisco Narciso de Laprida</strong> (deputy for San Juan): held the rotating presidency in July, and so was the man who put the independence question to the vote. (He would be killed in 1829 in Mendoza's civil wars (the subject of a famous Borges poem).)</li>
            <li><strong>Mariano Boedo</strong> (Salta): vice-president.</li>
            <li><strong>Manuel Belgrano</strong>: not a deputy, but arrived from Europe and addressed the Congress in a secret session on 6 July.</li>
            <li><strong>José de San Martín</strong>: not present; governor of Cuyo, he lobbied relentlessly by letter from Mendoza.</li>
            <li><strong>Juan Martín de Pueyrredón</strong>: elected Director Supremo, pushed the deputies to declare and then left for Buenos Aires.</li>
            <li><strong>Fray Cayetano Rodríguez</strong>: Franciscan, deputy for Buenos Aires, editor of the <em>Redactor</em>.</li>
            <li><strong>Fray Justo Santa María de Oro</strong>: deputy for San Juan, who insisted the form of government be submitted to the people, threatening to resign otherwise.</li>
          </ul>

          <h3 id="san-martin">San Martín's pressure and the "juridical" argument for independence</h3>
          <p>
            From Mendoza, where he was organizing the Army of the Andes, San Martín argued that the army needed to fight as the force of a declared sovereign state rather than as rebels still nominally subject to the king. His 12 April 1816 letter to deputy Tomás Godoy Cruz states:
          </p>
          <blockquote>
            <p>
              "How long are we going to wait to declare our independence! Doesn't it seem to you a ridiculous thing to mint coins, have a national flag and cockade, and finally to wage war on the sovereign on whom we believe we still depend? … The enemies (and with much reason) treat us as insurgents, since we declare ourselves vassals." (<a href="https://www.educ.ar/recursos/128506/carta-de-jose-de-san-martin-a-tomas-godoy-cruz" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">educ.ar transcription</a>; Mendoza, 12 April 1816)
            </p>
          </blockquote>
          <p>
            Historians often treat the declaration as a political act taken under military pressure, not as the tidy end of a process already complete.
          </p>

          <h3 id="session-9-july">The session of 9 July 1816</h3>
          <p>
            On Tuesday 9 July 1816, around 2 p.m., the deputies met in the adapted salon of the house of <strong>Francisca Bazán de Laguna</strong> on the calle del Rey (today calle Congreso 141). Teodoro Sánchez de Bustamante (Jujuy) moved to take up independence; after debate, President Laprida put the question (<a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Declaraci%C3%B3n_de_independencia_de_la_Argentina" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Wikipedia</a>; <a href="https://www.argentina.gob.ar/noticias/9-de-julio-de-1816-declaracion-de-la-independencia-de-la-argentina" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">argentina.gob.ar</a>):
          </p>
          <blockquote>
            <p>
              "Whether they wished the provinces of the Union to be a free and independent nation of the kings of Spain and their metropolis."
            </p>
          </blockquote>
          <p>
            The deputies answered affirmatively. The <a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Declaraci%C3%B3n_de_independencia_de_la_Argentina" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Acta de la Independencia</a> declared the "unanimous and indubitable will" of the provinces to break ties with the kings of Spain and to become a free and independent nation of King Ferdinand VII, his successors and metropolis. The declaring body is named the <strong>Congreso de las Provincias Unidas en Sud América</strong>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Number of signers</strong>: The Acta was signed by <strong>29 deputies</strong>. (Note the arithmetic that trips up many summaries: about 33–34 were elected, but 29 signed on/around 9 July.) Five elected deputies were absent that day: José Moldes (Salta, under arrest); Juan José Feliciano Fernández Campero (Chichas, commanding troops at the front); Miguel Calixto del Corro (Córdoba, on a diplomatic mission to Artigas); Pedro Buenaventura Carrasco (Cochabamba, serving in the Army of the North); and Pueyrredón himself (San Luis, gone to Buenos Aires to assume the Directorship).
          </p>

          <h3 id="foreign-domination">"…and of all other foreign domination": the 19 July addition</h3>
          <p>
            The 9 July text broke with Spain but said nothing about <em>other</em> powers. In the following days, rumors circulated that the Director Pueyrredón, General Belgrano and even some deputies were entertaining schemes to hand the country to Portugal (or, earlier, to Britain; Alvear had floated a British protectorate in 1815). Belgrano's own monarchy proposal fed these fears.
          </p>
          <p>
            On <strong>19 July 1816</strong>, in secret session, Buenos Aires deputy <strong>Pedro Medrano</strong> moved to amend the oath/Act: after independence from Ferdinand VII, his successors and metropolis, add <strong>"y de toda otra dominación extranjera"</strong>. The recorded purpose was to counter rumors of delivery to Portugal (<a href="https://elhistoriador.com.ar/9-de-julio-de-1816-declaracion-de-la-independencia/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">El Historiador</a>; <a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Declaraci%C3%B3n_de_independencia_de_la_Argentina" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Wikipedia</a>).
          </p>

          <h3 id="inca-monarchy">The monarchy-vs-republic debate and Belgrano's Inca prince</h3>
          <p>
            The <em>form of government</em> was left undecided. Contemporary accounts describe broad support at Tucumán for constitutional <strong>monarchy</strong> rather than a republic, then the dominant European form after Napoleon's fall. Some accounts name Tomás Godoy Cruz as a republican holdout (<a href="https://elhistoriador.com.ar/el-congreso-de-tucuman-y-la-declaracion-de-la-independencia-por-felipe-pigna/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Pigna</a>).
          </p>
          <p>
            On <strong>6 July 1816</strong>, in secret session, Belgrano (back from a European mission) argued that a "tempered" (constitutional) monarchy was likelier to win European recognition, and proposed crowning <strong>a descendant of the Incas</strong> with the capital at Cuzco. San Martín and Güemes supported the idea; Alto Perú deputies were also favorable (<a href="https://elhistoriador.com.ar/el-congreso-de-tucuman-y-la-declaracion-de-la-independencia-por-felipe-pigna/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">El Historiador</a>; <a href="https://www.educ.ar/recursos/130847/belgrano-y-el-proyecto-de-monarquia-incaica/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">educ.ar</a>).
          </p>
          <p>
            It failed amid porteño elite opposition, no agreed dynastic candidate (a brother of Túpac Amaru was an elderly prisoner in Cádiz) and racist objections recorded by contemporaries, including porteño deputy <strong>Tomás Manuel de Anchorena</strong>'s private remark about being governed "by a member of the caste of the chocolates," and porteño press mockery of a "dirty-footed king." Mitre later dismissed the plan in <cite>Historia de Belgrano</cite>. The Congress postponed the question; a durable republican constitution came in <strong>1853</strong> (<a href="https://elhistoriador.com.ar/el-congreso-de-tucuman-y-la-declaracion-de-la-independencia-por-felipe-pigna/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">El Historiador</a>).
          </p>

          <h3 id="translations">The Acta in Spanish, Quechua and Aymara</h3>
          <p>
            The Congress ordered the Acta printed in <strong>Quechua and Aymara</strong> as well as Spanish. On 29 July 1816 it asked the Directorio for 3,000 copies: 1,500 Spanish, 1,000 Quechua, 500 Aymara. The Gandarillas press in Buenos Aires printed them in August 1816 in bilingual double-column format; they appeared in the <em>Gazeta de Buenos Aires</em> (17 August 1816) and <em>El Redactor</em>. Preparation of the Quechua version is attributed to Charcas deputy <strong>José Mariano Serrano</strong>, though that does not prove he personally translated it (<a href="https://www.argentina.gob.ar/interior/archivo-general-de-la-nacion/traducciones-de-la-independencia" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">AGN</a>; <a href="https://www.infobae.com/sociedad/2021/07/09/la-declaracion-de-la-independencia-traducida-al-quechua-y-al-aymara-que-fracaso-y-termino-con-una-leccion-de-san-martin/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Infobae</a>).
          </p>
          <p>
            A <strong>guaraní</strong> version was proposed but not distributed while the Litoral was at war with Buenos Aires and unrepresented. Few indigenous-language copies survive (reports cite two or three Quechua and one Aymara); an Aymara copy was later exhibited at the Casa Histórica (<a href="https://www.argentina.gob.ar/interior/archivo-general-de-la-nacion/traducciones-de-la-independencia" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">AGN</a>).
          </p>

          <h3 id="after-declaration">After the declaration: the wider Spanish-American context</h3>
          <p>
            In January 1817 San Martín launched the <a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cruce_de_los_Andes" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Cruce de los Andes</a>. Common figures are ~4,000 regulars and 1,200 militia; Gerónimo Espejo's 1882 <cite>El paso de los Andes</cite> gives a full muster around 5,423 (3,778 troops and 1,392 auxiliaries), plus horses and mules. The campaign ended in victory at <strong>Chacabuco (12 February 1817)</strong>. Miriam Victoria Gomes (Biblioteca del Congreso) estimates that of about 2,500 Black soldiers who began the crossing, 143 returned alive (an estimate, not a census). The army could now claim to fight for a declared sovereign state, as San Martín had argued.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Congress went on to sanction Argentina's first constitution in <strong>1819</strong> (unitary and never applied) before dissolving in 1820 after the Battle of Cepeda. The name and territory of "las Provincias Unidas en Sud América" bore little resemblance to today's Argentina: it included the Alto Perú (Bolivia), whose deputy Serrano would later preside over the assembly that declared Bolivia's independence in 1825. Uruguay's independence, by contrast, is dated to 1828.
          </p>
          <h3 id="naming">The name "Argentina" comes later</h3>
          <p>
            In 1816 the relevant name was <strong>Provincias Unidas en Sud América</strong>. Ternavasio notes that "Sudamérica" itself expressed uncertainty about which provinces would actually fall under the new legal condition, especially since the Banda Oriental and Litoral did not sit in the Congress. The failed centralist constitution of <strong>1826</strong> used the label <strong>República Argentina</strong> and declared a representative republican form, but provincial rejection prevented a stable modern state (<a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Provincias_Unidas_del_R%C3%ADo_de_la_Plata" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Wikipedia</a>; <a href="https://repositorio.uca.edu.ar/bitstream/123456789/10002/1/sobre-denominaciones-republica-argentina.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">UCA on denominations</a>). Ternavasio's end point: only after Buenos Aires accepted the 1853 Constitution (after 1860) does the history of the Argentine Republic begin <em>stricto sensu</em>.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="part-ii" aria-labelledby="part-ii-heading">
          <h2 id="part-ii-heading">Part II — How the holiday evolved</h2>

          <h3 id="first-celebrations">The first celebrations (1816) and the 19th-century see-saw</h3>
          <p>
            The first celebrations began immediately. After the 9 July session ran late, people gathered around the house shouting "Viva la Patria"; formal festivities followed the next day. <a href="https://www.argentina.gob.ar/noticias/9-de-julio-dia-de-la-independencia-2" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Argentina.gob.ar</a> records an elite celebration on 10 July with Mass at San Francisco (and a ball at the Bazán de Laguna house / Governor Aráoz's home) and a popular celebration on 21 July at Campo de Carreras (symbolically important as the site of the Battle of Tucumán) with a reported 5,000-plus people and speeches by Belgrano and Aráoz. Treat this as local appropriation of the revolution as much as "everyone had a party."
          </p>
          <p>
            Ternavasio adds a holiday-history note: the <strong>Fiestas Mayas</strong> began in 1811 and were never cancelled; after 1816 the <strong>Fiestas Julias</strong> were added to commemorate independence, but 25 May almost always kept the privileged place in the Río de la Plata festive calendar, especially in Buenos Aires (<a href="https://www.educ.ar/recursos/130924/un-pais-con-dos-fechas-patrias" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Educ.ar / Ternavasio</a>). Contemporaries often gave May the deeper emotional priority because it marked the revolutionary rupture they had lived through; July later became the formal Independence Day.
          </p>
          <p>Through the 19th century, the holiday's fortunes rose and fell with politics:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>1826</strong>: Bernardino Rivadavia effectively demoted it: a decree of 6 July 1826 ordered that 9 July be commemorated jointly with 25 May, arguing that "the repetition of these festivities causes considerable harm to commerce and industry." In practice the "Fiestas Mayas" (25 May) were the paramount patriotic festival of the 1820s.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>1835</strong>: Juan Manuel de Rosas reversed this. His decree of 11 June 1835 declared that 9 July "should be no less celebrated than 25 May," restoring it to full festive rank (<a href="https://www.argentina.gob.ar/noticias/9-de-julio-dia-de-la-independencia-2" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">argentina.gob.ar</a>). Under Rosas the "Fiestas Julianas" gained importance; celebrations acquired a heavier religious component and federal red alongside celeste-y-blanco. Ternavasio notes that the May and July festivities of 1834 already incorporated homage to Rosas's 1833 desert expedition, bending civic holidays toward leader-cult politics.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>1866</strong>: the 50th anniversary passed without major celebration; the country was fighting the War of the Triple Alliance.
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h3 id="casa-historica">The Casa Histórica: demolition, the Templete and the 1943 reconstruction</h3>
          <p>
            The building's later history is well documented and often misstated in tourism copy.
          </p>
          <p>
            The house was built around 1760 by the Bazán-Laguna family, one of Tucumán's leading families; it was a substantial colonial <em>casona</em> of three parallel wings around patios, with a baroque portal flanked by twisted (salomonic) columns, <strong>not</strong> the tiny cottage that its affectionate nickname "Casita de Tucumán" implies. During the Congress, two rooms parallel to the façade were merged (by demolishing a dividing wall) to form the session hall, about 15 m by 5 m.
          </p>
          <p>
            After 1816 the house deteriorated in Tucumán's humid climate. By 1869 it was in ruins when the photographer <strong>Ángel Paganelli</strong> took the only known photographs of the original house, images that would later prove essential. An 1869 law (under Sarmiento) authorized nationalizing the house; the state bought it (1874), remodeled the façade and installed post-office and judicial offices.
          </p>
          <p>
            The near-fatal blow came under President <strong>Julio A. Roca</strong>: in <strong>1903 demolition began</strong> and in September <strong>1904</strong> everything was torn down <em>except</em> the "Salón de la Jura" (the room where independence was sworn), which was enclosed inside an ornate French-style pavilion called <strong>"El Templete"</strong>, with stained glass, bronze plaques and two bronze reliefs by the Tucumán sculptor Lola Mora commemorating 25 May 1810 and 9 July 1816. Isolating the salon inside that pavilion made it look like a tiny adobe house (one origin of the "casita" nickname) (<a href="https://www.lagaceta.com.ar/nota/691339/sociedad/historia-casa-tucuman-entro-historia.html" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">La Gaceta</a>; <a href="https://billiken.lat/interesante/como-fue-la-reconstruccion-de-la-casa-historica-de-tucuman-en-1943/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Billiken</a>).
          </p>
          <p>
            In <strong>1941</strong> the house was declared a National Historic Monument (12 August). A commission (Ricardo Levene and architects Martín Noel, Mario J. Buschiazzo and Alejandro Figueroa) proposed a full reconstruction. The Templete was demolished; architect <strong>Mario Buschiazzo</strong> directed the rebuild, using Paganelli's 1869 photographs and the 1870s survey plans and locating the original foundations underground. Period tiles, doors and grilles were bought from the (contemporaneous) Piedrabuena bishop's residence, then being demolished. The reconstructed house was inaugurated as a museum on <strong>24 September 1943</strong> (anniversary of the Battle of Tucumán), under the de facto government of General Pedro Pablo Ramírez.
          </p>
          <p>
            For decades the reconstruction was shown with yellow walls and green openings from a late-19th-century Genaro Pérez painting. A 1996 study by architect Juan Carlos Marinsalda of door paint layers concluded the 1816 openings were <strong>Prussian blue</strong> on white walls; that scheme has since been restored. The site is now the <a href="https://www.argentina.gob.ar/capital-humano/cultura/monumentos/museo-casa-historica-de-la-independencia" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Museo Nacional de la Independencia</a>.
          </p>

          <h3 id="centenario">The Centenario (1916): a subdued centennial</h3>
          <p>
            The 100th anniversary in 1916 was, by design or circumstance, muted. World War I had "closed the Atlantic," so no international guests came (a sharp contrast with the lavish, cosmopolitan 1910 centenary of the <em>May Revolution</em>). President Victorino de la Plaza did not even travel to Tucumán, sending a delegate. In Buenos Aires, after a Te Deum, the 9 July military parade was marred by a frustrated assassination attempt against the president by an anarchist. The moment was politically charged: Hipólito Yrigoyen had just been elected under the new Sáenz Peña secret-ballot law and the Radical era was beginning.
          </p>
          <p>
            Balmaceda and others note an asymmetry that stuck: 25 May is remembered more vividly than 9 July in popular culture, partly because May 1810 has better-known protagonists in schoolbooks (<a href="https://www.lanacion.com.ar/lifestyle/por-que-recordamos-mas-revolucion-mayo-nid2265816/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">La Nación</a>).
          </p>

          <h3 id="peron-1947">Perón and the "Economic Independence" of 1947</h3>
          <p>
            On <strong>9 July 1947</strong>, President Juan Domingo Perón held an act of <strong>Independencia Económica</strong> at the Casa Histórica. With Chilean president Gabriel González Videla present, Interior Minister Ángel Borlenghi read an "Acta de la Independencia Económica" pledging economic emancipation from "foreign capitalist powers," dated in San Miguel de Tucumán and framed as echoing 1816. The ceremony accompanied nationalizations and the First Five-Year Plan (<a href="https://www.infobae.com/sociedad/2023/07/09/el-otro-congreso-de-tucuman-el-dia-que-peron-declaro-la-independencia-economica-y-auguro-60-anos-sin-crisis/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Infobae</a>).
          </p>

          <h3 id="sesquicentenario">The Sesquicentenario (1966) and the dictatorships</h3>
          <p>
            The 150th anniversary in 1966 was overshadowed: President Arturo Illia had been preparing a major celebration when, on 28 June 1966, General Juan Carlos Onganía's coup overthrew him. No foreign guests came; the commemoration was reduced to a military parade on Avenida del Libertador.
          </p>
          <p>
            On <strong>5 February 1975</strong>, President María Estela Martínez de Perón (Isabel) signed Decree 261/75 authorizing <a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operativo_Independencia" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Operativo Independencia</a>, a military campaign in Tucumán against the ERP. From 9 February 1975 troops occupied the province. The <strong>"Escuelita de Famaillá"</strong> operated as a clandestine detention center; CONADEP and later official memory sites identify it as among the first of that type in the country (<a href="https://www.argentina.gob.ar/noticias/47-anos-del-operativo-independencia-espacio-para-la-memoria-ex-ccdtye-la-escuelita-de" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">argentina.gob.ar / Espacio Famaillá</a>). Estimates of people held there vary (Wikipedia cites ~1,507 for Famaillá; other provincial memory sources give ranges around 1,500–2,500). The operation's name and location remain contested in Argentine memory politics.
          </p>

          <h3 id="modern-ritual">Modern commemoration: the standard ritual</h3>
          <p>
            Contemporary 9 July commemorations are usually centered on Tucumán and include:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>A <strong>presidential visit to Tucumán</strong> and the Casa Histórica (in most years);</li>
            <li>The <strong>Tedeum</strong> (Te Deum mass) in the Cathedral of San Miguel de Tucumán;</li>
            <li>The <strong>izamiento</strong> (flag raising) in Plaza Independencia;</li>
            <li>The <strong>"chocolate patrio"</strong> (hot chocolate shared in the plaza in the winter morning);</li>
            <li>A <strong>desfile cívico-militar</strong> (civic-military parade) with the armed forces, gaucho associations, indigenous communities, immigrant collectivities and schools;</li>
            <li>Nationwide <strong>Te Deums, school pageants and flag displays</strong>. Under <a href="https://www.argentina.gob.ar/normativa/nacional/ley-27399-281835/texto" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Ley 27.399</a> (2017), 9 July is listed among Argentina's <strong>feriados nacionales inamovibles</strong> (immovable national holidays).</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            Then there is <strong>food</strong>. Because 9 July falls in the depth of the southern winter, the traditional dishes are hearty: <strong>locro</strong> first, plus empanadas, pastelitos, humita, tamales, carbonada and tortas fritas. Locro is a slow-cooked stew of white maize, beans, squash and various meats (its name is from Quechua <em>ruqru</em>/<em>luqru</em>), of pre-Hispanic Andean origin, later enriched with the pork, beef and sausage brought by the Spanish. It is eaten on both national dates, 25 May and 9 July.
          </p>
          <p>
            CONICET researcher Carina Perticone argues the "locro patrio" custom in Buenos Aires is largely 20th-century: there is little evidence it was eaten there around independence, and it only became the dominant patriotic dish around 1960, displacing rivals such as carbonada ("a construction, but not an arbitrary one") (<a href="https://www.iprofesional.com/actualidad/339869-por-que-comemos-locro-el-25-de-mayo-te-dejamos-una-super-receta" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">iProfesional interview</a>).
          </p>

          <h3 id="bicentenario">The Bicentenario (2016)</h3>
          <p>
            On <strong>9 July 2016</strong>, President Mauricio Macri attended the Tucumán ceremonies, signed an agreement with governors at the Casa Histórica and hosted Spain's emeritus king <a href="https://www.lanacion.com.ar/politica/el-saludo-de-mauricio-macri-al-rey-emerito-juan-carlos-de-espana-durante-los-festejos-por-el-bicentenario-nid1916943/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Juan Carlos I</a>. Official estimates reported by the press put the Mate de Luna parade crowd above 400,000; a second parade was held in Buenos Aires (<a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bicentenario_de_la_Independencia_de_Argentina" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Wikipedia: Bicentenario</a>). Coverage noted protests over economic policy, debate over costs and objections to some parade participants linked to Operativo Independencia. Macri's speech framed independence around Tucumán without mentioning May 1810 (an example of the 1810/1816 conflation).
          </p>

          <h3 id="milei-years">The Milei years (2024–2026): attendance, absence and museum dispute</h3>
          <p>
            Under President Javier Milei (in office since December 2023), 9 July events have again been used for national political messaging.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>2024</strong>: Milei attended and signed the <strong>"Pacto de Mayo,"</strong> a 10-point governing accord, at the Casa Histórica with 18 of 24 governors/city heads; six did not sign (Kicillof, Insfrán, Ziliotto, Quintela, Melella, Vidal). Ex-presidents Macri and Rodríguez Saá attended. Milei's speech framed the pact as patriotic and criticized absentees (<a href="https://chequeado.com/el-explicador/a-un-ano-de-la-firma-del-pacto-de-mayo-el-chequeo-a-los-10-compromisos-del-acuerdo-que-hizo-javier-milei-con-los-gobernadores/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Chequeado summary</a>; <a href="https://www.casarosada.gob.ar/informacion/discursos/50568-palabras-del-presidente-javier-milei-en-la-firma-del-pacto-de-mayo" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Casa Rosada speech</a>).
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>2025</strong>: On the afternoon of 8 July, Milei cancelled the Tucumán trip, citing fog/weather; spokesman Manuel Adorni said Casa Militar and Air Force reports ruled out flights (<a href="https://tn.com.ar/politica/2025/07/08/debido-a-la-niebla-javier-milei-no-viajara-a-tucuman-por-el-9-de-julio/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">TN</a>). Press coverage also noted few governors had confirmed attendance and treated the weather explanation skeptically. Milei held an event in Buenos Aires instead. VP Victoria Villarruel was in Tucumán on a separate provincial invitation.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>2026</strong>: For the <strong>210th anniversary</strong>, Milei returned for the midnight Vigilia at the Casa Histórica (received by Governor Osvaldo Jaldo; accompanied by Karina Milei, Chief of Staff Diego Santilli and Economy Minister Luis Caputo), signed protocolary acts, and gave a cadena nacional speech comparing his program to an "economic crossing of the Andes" and calling for a "second independence." Press tallies of attending governors vary (about 11–13). He then led the Tedeum in Buenos Aires. VP Villarruel again attended separately in Tucumán. The daytime provincial program followed the usual schedule (chocolate patrio, flag raising, Tedeum, parade).
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Museum staffing dispute</strong>: In May 2024 the national government removed competitively appointed director Cecilia Guerra Orozco and installed interim director José María Posse, who criticized the prior "ideological orientation." A Tucumán outlet (Enterate Noticias), citing Secretaría de Cultura figures, reported a ~54% real budget cut for the museum between 2023 and 2025 (a single-source figure). Historians' association AsAIH issued a July 2025 statement opposing director removals at the Casa Histórica and other national museums. Posse disputed dismissal/budget claims and resigned in April 2026. Critic Camila Perochena accused the government of turning museums into partisan spaces; the government said it was removing ideological bias. Treat these as contested claims from opposing camps.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="myths" aria-labelledby="myths-heading">
          <h2 id="myths-heading">Myths, legends and things that need qualifying</h2>
          <p>Documented record versus common folklore:</p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <strong>"Argentina became Argentina on 9 July 1816."</strong> The declaration was by the Provincias Unidas en Sud América; the modern Argentine Republic consolidated later, especially after the constitutional settlement of 1853–1860 (Ternavasio; <a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Provincias_Unidas_del_R%C3%ADo_de_la_Plata" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Wikipedia</a>).
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>"The revolution was simply Argentina vs Spain."</strong> Early conflict was also civil war inside the old imperial order: cities vs capital, provinces vs provinces, Americans vs peninsulares, federalists vs centralists (Ternavasio).
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>"July 9 was always the obvious main patriotic holiday."</strong> May 25 had an earlier and often more privileged place in the revolutionary calendar; July was added after 1816 (<a href="https://www.educ.ar/recursos/130924/un-pais-con-dos-fechas-patrias" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Educ.ar / Ternavasio</a>).
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>"The Congress represented all of modern Argentina."</strong> Several provinces did not participate (especially the Litoral under Artigas) while Charcas (today Bolivia) did (<a href="https://www.educ.ar/recursos/132481/9-de-julio-dia-de-la-declaracion-de-la-independencia" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Educ.ar</a>).
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>"Independence meant republicanism was settled."</strong> Monarchy, including Belgrano's Inca proposal, was seriously debated after 1816.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>"The Casita de Tucumán."</strong> The diminutive is misleading. The house was a large, high-status colonial <em>casona</em> with a baroque salomonic-columned portal, not a humble cottage. The "little house" image is largely an artifact of the 1904 Templete, which visually isolated the surviving salon and made it look tiny. The building tourists visit today is a <strong>1943 reconstruction</strong>, not the original fabric, faithful to the 1869 Paganelli photographs, but a reconstruction nonetheless, with brick walls where the original had rammed earth.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>The colors.</strong> School-pageant depictions in yellow-and-green derive from a 19th-century painting, not reality. Documentary study (1996) established white walls with <strong>Prussian-blue</strong> (celeste) openings as the 1816 colors.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>"29 vs 33/34 deputies."</strong> These figures are routinely muddled. The best reading: roughly 33–34 deputies were elected/seated over the Congress's life; <strong>29 signed</strong> the Acta on/around 9 July 1816; five elected members were absent that day for specific documented reasons. Do not say "29 deputies were elected."
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>The lost original.</strong> The original signed Act, recorded in the Congress's book of public-session minutes, is genuinely lost, most likely moved to the Buenos Aires Legislature around 1820 and later stolen. What survives are contemporary printed copies (in the Archivo General de la Nación) and Serrano's copy. This does not undermine the declaration's authenticity, which rests on multiple copies and records. There is also a colorful, well-documented episode of the courier (Cayetano Grimau y Gálvez) being intercepted in Córdoba by an Artiguista party while carrying the Act toward Buenos Aires.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>"Argentina declared its independence."</strong> Strictly, the Act declares the independence of <strong>"las Provincias Unidas en Sud América,"</strong> a larger and different entity than today's Argentina (it included the Alto Perú). The name "Argentina" and the modern territory came later.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>May 1810 = independence.</strong> The single most common conflation, repeated even by presidents (Macri in 2016). 1810 = autonomy/first local government under the "mask of Ferdinand VII"; 1816 = formal independence and sovereignty.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Inca monarchy as a fringe footnote.</strong> Popular retellings treat Belgrano's proposal as eccentric. Contemporary evidence shows substantial monarchist support at Tucumán and backing from San Martín, Güemes and Alto Perú deputies; it failed for political and social reasons, not because it was a joke (<a href="https://elhistoriador.com.ar/el-congreso-de-tucuman-y-la-declaracion-de-la-independencia-por-felipe-pigna/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">El Historiador</a>).
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>The "Hawái recognized Argentina first" story.</strong> A romantic claim (tied to Hipólito Bouchard and King Kamehameha I) circulates widely; it should be treated with skepticism as popular legend rather than established diplomatic fact.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Montoneros graffiti photos.</strong> Photos circulated claiming Montoneros inscriptions on the Salón walls; <a href="https://chequeado.com/el-explicador/son-falsas-las-fotos-que-circulan-de-la-casa-de-tucuman-con-inscripciones-de-montoneros-se-trata-de-un-montaje/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Chequeado</a> identified them as montages (related to a 2021 art-work controversy, not fresh vandalism of the walls).
            </li>
          </ol>
        </section>

        <section id="caveats-figures" aria-labelledby="caveats-figures-heading">
          <h2 id="caveats-figures-heading">Caveats on conflicting figures and accounts</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Number of deputies</strong>: Educ.ar gives <strong>33 present</strong> at the 24 March 1816 opening; other secondary sources give ~33–34 elected over the Congress's life and sometimes ~21 on opening day. Prefer Educ.ar for the opening count; <strong>signers of the Acta = 29</strong> (stable). Clergy among signers: 11 or 12; lawyers: 17 or 18.</li>
            <li><strong>Date the Congress moved to Buenos Aires</strong>: the <em>decision</em> to move was voted 25 September 1816 (vote reported as 28–4); the Congress's last Tucumán session is dated variously to 16 January or 4 February 1817; it reconvened in Buenos Aires in April/May 1817.</li>
            <li><strong>Wording of the question</strong>: sources give slightly different phrasings ("¿Si quieren que las provincias de la Unión fuesen una nación libre e independiente de los reyes de España y su metrópoli?" vs. "¿Queréis que las provincias de la Unión sean una nación libre e independiente…?"). These are transcription variants of the <em>Redactor</em> text.</li>
            <li><strong>The "toda otra dominación extranjera" date</strong>: consistently 19 July 1816 (secret session), on Medrano's motion, though the argentina.gob.ar phrasing loosely says "ten days later" (counting from 9 July).</li>
            <li><strong>Print run of the Acta</strong>: consistently reported as 3,000 total (1,500 Spanish / 1,000 Quechua / 500 Aymara), Gandarillas press, August 1816.</li>
            <li><strong>Guaraní translation</strong>: proposed and possibly prepared, but not distributed; some tourism/government pages loosely say the Act was "translated into Quechua, Aymara and Guaraní," which overstates the guaraní case.</li>
            <li><strong>Army of the Andes size</strong>: the crossing force is usually given as ~4,000 regulars + 1,200 militia; the full muster (including auxiliaries and civilian staff) is reported at ~5,423 by Espejo (1882). The figure of 143 Black soldiers repatriated alive comes from the Biblioteca del Congreso (Miriam V. Gomes) and is an estimate.</li>
            <li><strong>Casa demolition/reconstruction dates</strong>: demolition 1903–1904; Monument declaration 1941 (12 August); reconstruction works 1942; museum reopening 24 September 1943. Some sources compress "1904" and "1943"; the Templete stood 1904–1942.</li>
            <li><strong>2026 governor attendance</strong>: reported between 11 and 13, likely reflecting who was physically present vs. represented by vice-governors.</li>
            <li><strong>Casa Histórica budget cut (54%, 2023→2025)</strong>: from a single Tucumán outlet citing official data; directionally corroborated by the broader documented culture/memory cuts, but the precise percentage should be treated as one source's figure.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="caveats" aria-labelledby="caveats-heading">
          <h2 id="caveats-heading">Caveats</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>Built from Argentine online sources (heritage pages, newspapers, academic PDFs); not checked against physical AGN / <em>Redactor</em> / Buschiazzo files. Quoted wordings are transcribed from secondary sources.</li>
            <li>Outlets on Operativo Independencia and recent museum politics often have clear political slants; contested claims are attributed to named sources.</li>
            <li>2025–2026 political details rest on news reporting; the ~54% museum budget figure and 2026 governor tallies are the least-corroborated numbers here.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

